n><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> academies and free school</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">s. This submission is, therefore, intended to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">be considered alongside</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> more detailed local authorit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">y </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">evidence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">1.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Regardless of stance towards academies, it is a fact that under the current Government, the number of academies in the South East has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">increased</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. Between 2011/12 and 2012/13 no SESL authority saw a drop in the percentage of pupils educated in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">secondary academies, although growth has varied across the region. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The introduction of academies and free schools has changed the education landscape and raised questions about the role and responsibilities of local authorities in education and, in particu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">lar, in respect to academies and free schools.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">1.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">SESL has determined to submit a collective response as whilst South East Councils hold different positions on the concept of academies, we hold firmly that local authorities retain a role in promoting learnin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">g across all schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. We</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> recognise the need for the local authority as a strong ‘Middle Tier’ between all schools and the Secretary of State. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We agree that:</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.9pt; padding-left:15.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Local authorities continue to have an important role as those responsible for promoting learning </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">and the fulfilment of potential of all pupils across all education providers.</span></li></ul></ul></ul><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.5pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-heig