ate with local authorities.</span></li></ul></ul></ul><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.9pt; padding-left:15.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">There may be value in the Committee exploring what securi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">ties convertor academies either need or already have in place to guard against possible future deterioration or failure. </span></li></ul></ul></ul><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.5pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.9pt; padding-left:15.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><a name="OLE_LINK3"></a><a name="OLE_LINK4"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Real time data and information sharing is a prerequisite to proactive intervention.</span></a></li></ul></ul></ul><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.9pt; padding-left:15.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">The capacity of local authorities to exercise d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">ue diligence towards all schools regardless of status is diminishing. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">SESL questions whether existing funding is sufficient to sustain required local authority capacity. </span></li></ul></ul></ul><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.9pt; padding-left:15.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">The attitude of some academy sponsors can make it difficult for local authorities to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> know their schools well. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">DfE and Regional</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Commissioners should encourage sponsors to engage constructively with local authorities directly and support their schools to do likewise. </span></li></ul></ul></ul><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.5pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 16.68pt; padding-left:1.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">Main submission</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Local authorities have an on-going role in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">promoting learning</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">2.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The duties placed on English local authorities under Section 13 of the Education Act 1996, relating to promoting high standards of education, ensuring fair access to opportunity and promoting the fulfilment of learning potential, apply</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">all</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> children and young people across </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">all</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> schools and alternative education providers, which includes academies. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Whilst there is some debate as to the exten</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> to which a local authority is ‘capable</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> of exercising </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">these functions with respect to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">non-maintained schools, academies are not independent fro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">m these local authority duties.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">2.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">As long as these duties remain, local authorities have a role to engage constructively with, and seek to influence, all schools to ensure their responsibilities towar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ds children are being met. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">South East Councils continue to relate to all schools in carrying out responsibilities for admissions, SEN exclusions and commissioning new school places. I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">n respect to championing vulnerable pupils and ensuring equality of oppor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">tunity, for example, there are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">cases</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> of South East Councils taking a very active role. In Kent, the County Council and local schools are focusing intensively on narrowing the attainment gap for vulnerable groups. In the same way as local authority maintain</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ed schools, Kent County Council expects academies to focus on ensuring that vulnerable groups are identified, strategies personalised and pupil premium monies effectively targeted. </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">To fulfil their role successfully, councils need to build strong relation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ships with all schools</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">2.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Establishing strong relationships</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> is a prerequisite to constructive engagement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> with any school.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Where </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">a local authority</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> do</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">es</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> have direct powers of intervention, these are often only effective where </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">that local authority</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> the capacity to invest in building constructive relationships with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">its </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">schools and the history of doing so. Nurturing strong, positive, trusting relationships with academies </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">is important as t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">he quality of relationship</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> is likely to determine the level of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">information shared by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">academies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> with their local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">counci</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">2.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Across </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">SESL </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">there are many examples of where local authorities have invested in build</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ing positive relationships with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">in a variety of ways. To give one example, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">through collaboration with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Robert Bloomfield Academy, Central Bedfordshire Council has established The Central Bedfordshire Teaching School Partnership and Council </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Commissioning Officers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> sit on the Partnership’s Strategic Board. </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">2.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The partnership has published an on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">line workforce </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">development tool</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and is helping to broker school-to-school support using National and Local Leaders of Education and Governance, Advanced Skills Teachers and Specialist Leaders. Central Bedfordshire already has four National Leaders in Governance. The Coun</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">cil would like to approach other Chairs but </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> been prevented from doing so due to tight, nationally imposed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">qualifying criteria</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> regarding length of service prior to applying</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. The Committee may wish to see if this is an issue for other areas and subsequen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">tly to explore loosening the criteria on qualifying Governors. </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Where relationships are not good, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Government should support councils to exercise their democratic mandate.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">2.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">There exist a number of means by which local authorities can seek to influence academies; for example, through meeting with the Chairs of overarching Trusts and regular meetings with regional HMI. There are many examples of positive endeavour on this front</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. In Kent, for example, the local authority has been inviting academies to work in partnership with other schools to create a sustainable, self-improvement school system, which is working well. Despite many examples of positive engagement, difficulties can</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and do arise where, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">for whatever reason, an academy refuses to engage constructively with the local authority.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">2.7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Persistent un-cooperation and disengagement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">can</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> lead to a situation where it becomes difficult for a local authority to be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> a)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> assured of the health of a school and thus to fulfil its statutory duties towards pupils</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and b) to drive improvement within that school</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">In the current system, where relationships break down and attempts to influence through exerting soft powers fail, it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">is the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">DfE’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> responsibility to intervene and drive necessary improvements at pace. It would therefore be prudent for the Committee to explore further whether the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> has the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">local knowledge </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">of underperforming academies and the capacity </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">and capability </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">to in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">tervene quickly and support sustained improvement.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> The decision to recruit Schools Commissioners in eight regions across the country and to charge them with responsibility for monitoring performance and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">driving improvement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">underperforming academies impl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ies that there is a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">gap not currently being met by the Department. </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">2.8.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">In keeping with localism, it is essential that local politicians, alongside their schools, are able to be held to account by their communities for the education that their children and yo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ung people receive</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Local politicians are far better placed than Whitehall or any regional representative to keep abreast of and address local issues.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Indeed, when difficulties arise, residents rarely turn first to the Secretary of State bu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> rather to thei</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">r locally elected politicians. Local Councillors need to be supported to influence schools and to hold providers to account for the delivery of the local system through their democratic mandate.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">2.9.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">To this end, Regional Schools Commissioner</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> should be required to cooperate with local authorities, sharing information about underperforming academies </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">with which they are working and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">involving </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">local authorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">both </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">discussions about the most appropriate remedial action and securing school impr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ovement services. Local authorities, have a wealth of local knowledge, practical expertise and experience in this area that Regional Commissioners ought to draw upon. In light of Councils’ broad systems oversight</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and democratic mandate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, Commissioners ought</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> also to involve them in decisions to approve an academy conversion application. </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">2.10.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Local Councillors could be further supported to exercise their democratic mandate by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">structuring the Funding Agreement between the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">cademies in a way that reinforces</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> to academies that whilst they are funded centrally, they have a responsi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">bility towards locally elected M</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">embers. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-indent:21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Convertor academies – a potential line for future enquiry</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">2.11.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The principle that no school is beyond falling into difficulties is an impor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">tant one and raises </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">questions around convertor academies. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Whi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">lst we celebrate in the successes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> of such schools, we have concerns regarding the longevity of that success and the potential vulnerability of convertor academies in particular. We suggest there </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">is value in the Committee exploring the basis of convertor academy success, whether their success is likely to be sustained</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and what securities are needed/exist</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> that will help</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> convertor academies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> to guard against potential deterioration or failure in the f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">uture. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Being proactive, not reactive relies on access to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">real time</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> information and data </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">sharing</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">2.12.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Local authorities have a role, alongside an array of other partners, to support schools throughout their improvement journey. This involves identifying and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">acting upon early warning signs that might, for example, suggest that educational standards are slipping.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Councils’ ability to track individual pupil data </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">in real time, over a period of time, is important to spotting warning signs. Local authorities ought </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">not to be in a position where they must wait for the Department to publish Key Stage data, for example, several months after it is received by local schools; rather, they need access to robust, real time information before it is placed in the public domain</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Access to more sensitive information also plays an important part in supporting councils to fulfil their safeguarding responsibilities.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">2.13.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">As referenced above, building strong relationships with schools overtime will underpin </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">willingness to share</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">information. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">cross the South East there are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">examples of locally negotiated information sharing protocols between </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ouncils and academies which are proving effective. For locally-led initiatives, such as the Troubled F</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">amilies Programme, there may be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> need f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">or further </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">data sharing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> within locally agreed timescales. </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Academy sponsors should be strongly encouraged to cooperate with councils and encourage their schools to do likewise.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">2.14.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">It is sometimes the case that academies, which enjoy a good relationship with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> their local authority and are open to sharing information in principle, come under pressure from their Sponsor not</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> share data with their local authority. This causes unnecessary obstacles locally which could be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> easily overcome if nationally </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">academy spo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">nsors were encouraged</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> by the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> in the future</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Regional Schools Commissioners</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> to willingly and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">constructively </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">engage with local authorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> directly. Moreover, Sponsors should actively encourage academies within their sphere to communicate with their local authority. </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The capacity of local authorities to exercise due diligence towards all schools, regardless of status, is diminishing</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="color:#808080; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">2.15.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">It is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">increasingly difficult for local authorities to know all of their schools well due to limited capacity and SESL questions whether existing </span><a name="OLE_LINK5"></a><a name="OLE_LINK6"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">funding </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> sufficient to sustain the capacity of local authorities to exercise due diligence with their schools, rega</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">rdless of status. </span></a></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#808080; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#808080; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:9pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:9pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#808080; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:9pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#808080; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:9pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#808080; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:9pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#808080; font-family:Arial;